&gt; 
&gt; Um. Okay.
&gt; 
&gt; Here&#39;s a sample test method:
&gt;     public void testGetMerchantId() throws java.rmi.RemoteException 
{
&gt;         obtainMerchant(&quot;Merchant1&quot;);
&gt;         assertEquals(&quot;Merchant1&quot;, getSample().getMerchantId());
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt; Here&#39;s a smart implementation of obtainMerchant:
&gt;     protected void obtainMerchant(String merchantId) {
&gt;       if (EjbHelper.isLive()) {
&gt;           try {
&gt;               javax.ejb.EJBHome ejbHome =
&gt; EjbHelper.lookupHome(MERCHANT_HOME, MerchantHome.class);
&gt;               MerchantHome home = (MerchantHome)ejbHome;
&gt;               
&gt;               setSample(home.create(merchantId));
&gt;           }
&gt;           catch (javax.ejb.CreateException e) {
&gt;               throw new RuntimeException(&quot;CreateException: &quot; +
&gt; e.getMessage());
&gt;           }
&gt;           catch (javax.naming.NamingException e) {
&gt;               throw new RuntimeException(&quot;NamingException: &quot; +
&gt; e.getMessage());
&gt;           }
&gt;           catch (java.rmi.RemoteException e) {
&gt;               throw new RuntimeException(&quot;RemoteException: &quot; +
&gt; e.getMessage());
&gt;           }
&gt;       }
&gt;       else {
&gt;         return new MerchantImpl(merchantId);
&gt;       }
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt; (EjbHelper is a utility class, but it should be fairly obvious what 
it does,
&gt; from context). About the only thing that&#39;s not clear is that
&gt; EjbHelper.isLive() returns Boolean.getBoolean(&quot;EJB_LIVE_MODE&quot;), 
allowing EJB
&gt; testing to be turned on or off by supplying a system property.
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; Any other tips and practical issues regarding testing and EJB 
would
&gt; &gt; be great.
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;ll see what I can come up with.
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; I have heard that this (testing locally and then live) is not
&gt; &gt; nessesary with Visual Age since you can run your appserver within
&gt; &gt; Visual Age...? Is this true?
&gt; 
&gt; Technically, this is true, or so I&#39;m told. When I was playing with 
EJB 1.0,
&gt; I didn&#39;t have Visual Age. When I had Visual Age, I&#39;d moved on to 
EJB 1.1,
&gt; which VAJ doesn&#39;t support. However, I&#39;ve got a goal of being able 
to run my
&gt; unit tests from the command line, via Ant, so I wouldn&#39;t want to 
rely on
&gt; such support, anyway (though it would be handy for the odd debugging
&gt; session).
&gt; 
&gt; However, VAJ doesn&#39;t like more than one person working on an EJB 
group (a
&gt; collection of related EJBs) at a time (it will actually end up 
corrupting
&gt; the repository, given enough time, and will produce all sorts of 
weird side
&gt; effects in the interim). If you&#39;re working by yourself, that&#39;s not a
&gt; problem. If you&#39;re working with others, it&#39;s nasty. There&#39;s a 
review on
&gt; theserverside.com, by Bartek Kiepuszewski (a former co-worker of 
mine),
&gt; which details all the hassles we had doing EJB development in VAJ 
and
&gt; WebSphere. (http://theserverside.com/reviews/thread.jsp?
thread_id=2974)
